This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the analysis of neuroimaging data using deep learning methods. The use of sparse autoencoders and 3D convolutional neural networks also suggests that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the study involves the prediction of Alzheimer's disease, which is related to neuroscience (cs.NE) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-categories.
